==German==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|goh|de}} {{term|bī|lang=goh}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|de}} {{m|gem-pro|*bi}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/baɪ/|lang=de}}
* {{rhymes|aɪ|lang=de}}
* {{audio|De-bei.ogg|audio|lang=de}}

===Preposition===
{{head|de|preposition|+ dative}}

# {{context|with something that has a location|lang=de}} [[by]] (some place or someone); [[near]]; [[with]]; [[on]]
#: ''Ich habe es nicht '''bei''' mir.'' — “I do not have it on me.”
# {{context|with something that has a definite time|lang=de}} [[by]] (some time); by the beginning of (some event); [[at]]; [[on]]; [[upon]]
#: '''''bei''' Abfahrt des Zuges'' — “upon departure of the train”
# {{context|with something that has a duration|lang=de}} [[during]]; [[while]]; [[over]]
#: '''''bei''' der Arbeit'' — “during work”
#: '''''bei''' einem Glase Wein'' — “over a glass of wine”
# {{context|with a person, business name, or job title|lang=de}} at the home, business, or station usually occupied by (someone)
# {{context|with an organization|lang=de}} [[in]]; [[for]]
#: '''''bei''' der Firma arbeiten'' — “to work for the firm”
# {{context|with something that may or may not occur|lang=de}} [[if]] there is (something)
#: '''''bei''' Schnee'' — “if there is snow”
# {{context|in a postal address|lang=de}} [[care of]]
# {{context|now|_|dialectal|nonstandard|western and northern Germany|with '''accusative'''|lang=de}} [[with]], [[to]], [[towards]]
#: ''Leg dat '''bei''' die andern Sachen!'' – Put that with the other things!
#: ''Komm ma '''bei''' mich!'' – Come to me!

====Usage notes====
* When {{term|bei}} is followed by the definite article {{term|dem||the|lang=de}}, the two words contract to {{term|beim|lang=de}}. However, when {{term|dem|lang=de}} is a demonstrative pronoun, no contraction occurs. Compare:
:: ''Der Baum steht zu nah '''beim''' Haus.'' – “The tree is too close to the house.”
:: ''Der Baum steht zu nah '''bei dem''' Haus da hinten.'' – “The tree is too close to that house over there.”
* {{sense|with, to, towards}} In many dialects, and historically in literary style, {{term|bei}} could express movement, requiring then the accusative case. This is in conflict with modern standard rules, for which reason this usage has become rather rare. Note, however, that the adverb {{term|dabei|lang=de}} is still common in regional speech: ''Kommt noch was '''dabei'''?'' – “Do you want anything else with that?” (Where standard German would use {{term|dazu|lang=de}}). — Relicts of such usage in the standard language are, among many others, {{term|herbei|lang=de}}, {{term|beifügen|lang=de}}, {{term|beilegen|lang=de}}, {{term|beitreten|lang=de}}. Compare also the idiom “{{term|Butter bei die Fische|lang=de}}”. Compare further {{etym|nl|-}} {{term|bij|lang=de}} for which all such constructions are perfect standard.

